On 06/23/2010 08:35 AM, Dário Abdulrehman wrote:
&lt;blockquote
 cite=&quot;mid:AANLkTin1QEf0TGHuX9LlLNsT5J8AMYyjHkX40rpx6xzQ@...&quot;
 type=&quot;cite&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: none;&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;

  &lt;div id=&quot;ygrp-text&quot;&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;I have one resource which is an algorithm that can receive a
potentially large input, say, a thousand arguments.&lt;br&gt;
GET my-algorithm?&lt;wbr&gt;x1=1&amp;x2=2....&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
I encountered some problems due to URI length limits imposed by Web
servers, even though the HTTP protocol does not set any limits on GET
request length.&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
The easiest solution is to expose the resource using POST instead of
GET but this violates REST principles, and the semantics of POST (I am
using POST when I mean GET).&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
The other alternative is to divide the interaction in 2 steps:&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
1 - POST my-algorithm/&lt;wbr&gt;args x1=1&amp;x2=2....&lt;br&gt;
     This creates a resource that represents the algorithm&#39;s arguments
we want to pass:&lt;br&gt;
     201 Created&lt;br&gt;
     location: /my-algorithm/&lt;wbr&gt;args/args-&lt;wbr&gt;resource-&lt;wbr&gt;1&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
2 - GET /my-algorithm/&lt;wbr&gt;args/args-&lt;wbr&gt;resource-&lt;wbr&gt;1&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
This solution seems to be more RESTful but I fear it will complicate
the interaction and potentially break statelessness (how long should
the server keep the arguments just posted?).&lt;br&gt;
I am really tempted to follow the first solution even though it
violates REST principles because I don&#39;t see any drawbacks and it
simplifies interaction.&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
I would appreciate some comments and suggestions.&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
Thank you.&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;


